{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 21:07:10.114227", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — SDN Spine–Leaf Lab\n\nScope and topology context\n- Switches: leaf_1, leaf_2 (OVS leafs), spine_1 (OVS spine), all managed by an SDN controller at 20.0.0.100 over OpenFlow (connected, fail_mode=secure).\n- Hosts: host_1_1 (10.0.0.1), host_1_2 (10.0.0.2) on leaf_1; host_2_1 (10.0.0.5), host_2_2 (10.0.0.6) on leaf_2; all in the same L2 subnet 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Physical links show as LIVE on all relevant OVS ports.\n\n1) Health assessment and anomalies detected\n- Severe L2 data-plane impairment:\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2 ping timed out (same leaf; should succeed on L2).\n  - host_1_1 -> host_2_1 ping timed out (inter-leaf).\n  - host_2_1 -> host_2_2 returned “Destination Host Unreachable” from 10.0.0.5 (sender), indicating ARP resolution failure on the local segment.\n- Management plane healthy:\n  - All switches have management IPs on 20.0.0.0/24 and report Controller is_connected: true.\n  - All involved OVS data-plane ports (eth0–eth3 and more) report state LIVE.\n\n2) Evidence and technical findings\n- Host interfaces and routing:\n  - All four hosts have correct 10.0.0.0/24 IPs on eth0, links up, and on-link routes present. No default gateways (expected for flat L2).\n- OVS control-plane and configuration:\n  - Controller connected on all three OVS bridges; fail_mode=secure (no learning fallback if controller logic is wrong).\n- OVS port-state (OpenFlow13) on all switches:\n  - Leaf and spine ports are LIVE, indicating no physical link-down condition.\n- OVS flow tables (critical):\n  - leaf_1 contains a rule: in_port=1 actions=output:1 (i.e., frames arriving on port 1 are sent back out port 1). This is a hairpin/self-forward rule that prevents L2 forwarding to any other port on the same bridge.\n  - leaf_2 contains a similar rule: in_port=2 actions=output:2 (same issue on the second leaf).\n  - Both leaf switches have many exact-match dl_src/dl_dst rules forwarding to ports 5/6 (eth4/eth5). In the provided topology, hosts are on eth0/eth1 and uplinks are on eth2/eth3; eth4/eth5 are not part of the described host/uplink connectivity yet have large traffic counters and are commonly used as egress in flows.\n  - Flow entries reference several MAC addresses that do not belong to the four hosts (for example dl_dst=6a:7b:f8:62:d4:8a, dl_src=22:83:84:e5:5f:6b), while host MACs are f6:3b:a8:4d:fb:74 (host_1_1), 76:ac:3d:19:c3:15 (host_1_2), 22:10:f5:93:9e:07 (host_2_1), 9e:01:71:3d:54:bf (host_2_2). There are no straightforward learning/flood rules to enable ARP/unknown-unicast to reach peers.\n- Ping symptom correlation:\n  - “Destination Host Unreachable” from host_2_1 to host_2_2 implies ARP broadcast did not reach the peer; consistent with hairpin rules and misdirected forwarding preventing L2 broadcast/learning on leaf_2.\n  - Same-leaf traffic (host_1_1 <-> host_1_2) fails despite physical port LIVE state, consistent with leaf_1’s hairpin rule and no correct L2 bridging flows.\n\n3) Fault localization\n- Fault is localized to the leaf switches’ data-plane programming (leaf_1 and leaf_2). Even intra-leaf L2 connectivity is broken, so the spine is not the immediate cause.\n- Hosts appear correctly configured and operational; management plane is normal.\n- The controller is connected in secure mode and has installed incorrect OpenFlow rules on the leafs.\n\n4) Root cause analysis\n- Incorrect OpenFlow rules pushed by the SDN controller to the leaf switches:\n  - Hairpin/self-forward rules (in_port=X -> output:X) and lack of appropriate L2 learning/flooding/forwarding behavior block ARP and unicast between hosts on the same bridge.\n  - Numerous exact-match flows direct traffic to ports (eth4/eth5) that are not part of the described host/uplink topology and reference MACs not present on the four hosts, indicating the controller’s port/host mapping is out-of-sync with the actual topology or using an incorrect pipeline.\n- Because fail_mode=secure is active, OVS does not fall back to normal switching; thus, incorrect controller logic fully dictates the broken forwarding behavior.\n\nImpact\n- End-to-end connectivity across the 10.0.0.0/24 broadcast domain is broadly disrupted. Both same-leaf and inter-leaf communications fail due to blocked ARP/unknown-unicast and misdirected egress selection.\n- Management connectivity and OpenFlow control connections are unaffected.\n\nSummary\n- Anomaly: Widespread L2 forwarding failure (ARP and unicast) across the data plane.\n- Faulty devices: leaf_1 and leaf_2 (OVS bridges), due to their installed flow rules.\n- Root cause: Misprogrammed OpenFlow rules by the SDN controller (hairpin rules, wrong egress ports, flows for incorrect MACs), combined with fail_mode=secure preventing fallback learning.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 20339, "output_tokens": 4543, "total_tokens": 24882, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 14848}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3264}}}
